{{ja-kanjitab|つるぎ|yomi=k}}
{{IPAfont|⟨turuki<sub>1</sub>⟩}} → *{{IPAchar|/turukʲi/}} → {{IPAchar|/t͡suruɡi/}}

Shift from {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=つるぎ|-}} ''tsuruki'',<ref name="DJR"/><ref name="KDJ"/> itself of {{unk|ja|nocap=1}} derivation.

A surface analysis suggests that this might be a compound of {{m|ja|[[釣る]], [[吊る]]|tr=tsuru||to [[hang]], as at one's [[side]]}} + ''ki'', but there is no clear [[etymon]] for the ''ki'' portion. One possibility would be {{m|ja|牙||[[fang]]}}, read as ''kiba'' in modern {{etyl|ja|-}} but also appearing as ''ki'' in {{etyl|ojp|-}} contexts. Such usage might parallel the combined {{m|en|tooth}} and {{m|en|blade}} meanings of the term ''ha'', spelled more specifically as {{m|ja|歯||tooth}} and {{m|ja|刃||blade}}, with these two senses listed as [[cognate]]s in Japanese dictionaries.<ref name="DJR"/><ref name="KDJ"/>

More tentative suggestions have been connections to Austronesian, such as {{cog|tl|suligi||[[dart]], short [[spear]]}}, but such possibilities seem only [[speculative]] at present.

